Ford GoBike System Data Analysis¶

by Ohiri Emeka Emmanuel¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a dataset containing about 183,000 bike records and 16 features that clearly show details of how bikes are shared amongst riders.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There were 183412 number of rows and 16 number of columns in the dataset. There are two (2) columns with datetime data type, two (2) columns that are of integer data type, seven (7) cloumns with a float data type and five (5) cloumns with an object data type. It is certain that more columns will be created in my bid to effectively clean the data.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in finding out what features in the dataset are best for predicting that a rider will have to share his/her bike.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

My hypothesis is that riders that are old based on their birth_year may likely share a bike, user_type might also influence a riders decision to share a bike if they are on subscription, they might want to let other people use their bike when they are not making use of it. I also think that gender type will also prompt bike sharing but to a smaller degree as compared to member_birth_year. Duration might also cause one to share a bike which also might be affected by the start station and end station.

Univariate Exploration¶

First of, lets see the Distribution of time taken for rides (duration_sec)

In [8]:
# A histogram plot of duration_sec to get the frequency distribution
binsize = 500
bins = np.arange(0, df['duration_sec'].max()+binsize, binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = df, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bins)
plt.title('Distribution of Duration in Seconds')
plt.xlabel('Duration (secs)')
plt.ylabel('Number of Trips')
plt.axis([-500, 12000, 0, 100000])
plt.show()
In [9]:
# Distribution is skewd to the right. So let's put it on a log scale instead to get a proper view
log_binsize = 0.025
bins = 10 ** np.arange(2.4, np.log10(df['duration_sec'].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = df, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([500, 1e3, 2e3, 5e3, 1e4, 2e4], [500, '1k', '2k', '5k', '10k', '20k'])
plt.title('Log Distribution of Duration in Seconds')
plt.xlabel('Duration (Secs)')
plt.ylabel('Number of Trips')
plt.show()

The first visualization had shown duration_sec to be long tailed and not well distributed. Using log scale, when plotted, duration looks modal and skewed to the right. You can see that higher peaks of trip appeared between 500 - 1000k before a steady decline began to occur.

The birth year of members were given but the age wasn't. Up next, we will check the distribution of the member_birth_year.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The normal distribution of duration showed fewer bars, but when the log distribution was plotted, it showed high numbers between 500k - 1000k seconds. I had thought at first that duration (secs) of higher numbers would attain the highest number of trips. I was shocked to see that duration of member_birth_year around 2000 had the highest frequency of trips. I had expected older years to have more trip as riders whose years are around year 2000 and age below 30 I felt would rather use a car than ride a bicycle. The start_day and end_day has almost same frequency distribution. I was expecting a not so similar distribution. My plot shows that subscriber of male gender both had the highest count of rides in their respective columns. It is also a surprise that those who did not share a bike are actually more than those who did. I had thought that since the dataset explores the bike sharing system, those who shared their bike would be more. Therefore, the unusual points for me was the year distribution, age as I had to do feature engineering to get the age. The bike sharing trip also had unusual distribution.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

At first, I changed the data type of the start_time and end_time from object to datetime. The conversion was to get the appropraite data type which will be of a great help if I decide to do a feature engineering so as to get the days of trip, start day and end day. The start day and end day was created. I also had to perform a feature engineering on the year column to get age for further analysis. I had to substract the year column from the current year. As earlier stated, unusual findings were seen on the year, age, bike sharing trip and start day for rides and end day having same pattern.

In [19]:
def scatterplot(data, xvariable, yvariable):
    '''
    This function is to be used to
    create a scatterplot that shows
    correlation between two features in
    our dataset using 400 samples for clear 
    and concise visuals
    '''
    #plt.figure is used to set the dimension of our plots
    plt.figure(figsize=[15,6])
    #lets plot the regplot using seaborn
    sb.regplot(data=df.sample(400), x=xvariable, y=yvariable);
    #plt.title gives the graph a title
    plt.title(f'correlation between {xvariable} and {yvariable}'.title(), fontsize=14, weight = "bold")
    #plt.xlable gives the graph a label on the x axis
    plt.xlabel(xvariable.title(), fontsize=10, weight="bold")
    #plt.yvariable gives the graph a label on the y axis
    plt.ylabel(yvariable.title(),fontsize=10, weight="bold")

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ function for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid
    on a sample of 1000. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x=x, y=y, color=default_color)

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 10])
g = sb.PairGrid(data = df_samp, y_vars = ['duration_sec', 'age'], x_vars = categoric_vars,
                height = 3, aspect = 1.8)
g.map(boxgrid)
plt.show()

In [25]:
# plot function to plot not visible boxplots
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
def boxgraph(data, xvariable, yvariable, color):
    '''function to create a boxplot of duration_sec against other
    features for better understanding'''
    plt.figure(figsize = [10, 5])
    sb.boxplot(data = data, x = xvariable, y = yvariable, color = color)
    plt.ylim([-10, 5000])
    plt.xlabel(xvariable.title())
    plt.ylabel(yvariable.title())
    plt.title(f'Box plot of {xvariable} and {yvariable}'.title())
    plt.show()

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

There is less than 50% correlation between start_station_id and end_station_id while the relationship between member_birth_year and age is highly negetively correlated (100%). There is no correlation between duration_sec and start_station_id nor end_station_id. Customer user_type is seen to have more duration than Subscribers on the boxplot plotted with limited sample but then, checking the entire dataset, Subcribers are seen to have more duration. Other and female member_type are seen to have more percentage of trip duration than male members on the plotted limited samples but visualzing the entire dataset proved different.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

The relationship between start_station_latitude and end_station_latitude was about 99% (positive correlation) which came as a surprise as I was expecting less percentage correlation since the stations of starting and ending a trip was entirely different locations. Same degree of percentage was equally observed between start_station_longitude and end_station_longitude. The correlation between start_station_latitude and end_station_longitude was more than 50% negetively correlated (-0.68) and same degree of correlation was seen between end_station_latitude and start_station_longtitude, it seems both the start_station and end_station are both in the same geographical location.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Male gender showed higher percentage on both fronts (sharing and not sharing a bike). Though, there was a surge on Other gender type at age 60 among those who shared a bike. Users that subscribed, and are mostly men aged between 25 - 30 showed higher percentage in sharing a bike. I had expected the female gender or other to top the list.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Seeing the male gender top the list of those that actually shared a bike was a surprise to me. I had guessed that subscriber user_type may have an effect on why a user might want to share a bike, that hypothesis proved to be true. I was not expecting same day to top the start day and end day. Seeing a rider more than 140 years not sharing a bike is surprising too.

Conclusions¶

In general, male gender topped the list of those who shared and also did not share a bike during the trip. A good percent of persons around 60 years of age on the other gender also covered more duration in seconds.

Both the start station latitude and end station latitude has positive effect on our dataset, I guess this showed how smooth trip was. Same can also be said about their respective longitudes.

Younger people covered more distances when grouped but then, I was not expecting same group to top the chart when it came to bike sharing. I had expected persons of older age.

The oldest rider is a female rider aged more than 140 years and she rode on Monday, she also did not share a bike.

No user_type as a customer shared a bike. Why this is so baffles me but then, a small percentage of subscribed user_type shared a bike. The percentage of subscribe users that did not share a bike was higher than those of same user_type who did share a bike.

A summary of my analysis showed that longer duration does not guarantee that a rider will share a bike. Been older as a rider doesn't mean a rider will share a bike as it was evident that younger riders were the ones who shared a bike.
